column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRACTOR, SEMI TRAILER, PUP UNIT TRAVELING ON STRAIGHT TWO LANE HIGHWAY. DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED AND ALLOWED VEHICLE TO DRIFT OVER TO EDGE OF PAVEMENT.  DRIVER DISCOVERED HIS PROBLEM AND PULLED THE VEHICLE BACK TO THE LEFT INTO THE DRIVING LANE.  THE PUP TRAILER WHIPPED TO THE RIGHT, CAUSING TOP HEAVY TRAILER TO BREAK AWAY FROM DRAW BAR/AXLE ASSEMBLY AND THE TANK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE OFF THE ROAD.  WHEN THE TRACTOR SEMI TRAILER CAME TO A STOP, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A LEAK OF PRODUCT FROM THE LOADING HATCH.  THE DRIVER TIGHTENED THE KEEPERS THAT HOLD THE HATCH CLOSED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. APPROXIMATELY (25) GALLONS HAD LEAKED OUT.

WHILE REWORKING A TRAILER AND REARRANGING THE FREIGHT, OUR FREIGHT HANDLER WAS BACKING OUT OF THE TRAILER AND RUBBED AGAINST ONE OF TWO PAILS ON THE RIGHT TAIL END OF THE TRAILER.  THIS PAIL WAS PUSHED BACK AND GOT PINNED BETWEEN THE WALL OF THE TRAILER, THE FORKLIFT, THE DOCK PLATE AND A BUNDLE OF STEEL IN FRONT OF IT.  THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED AND THE AREA CORDONED OFF. I CALLED CHEMTREC, THEY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER.  OUR SAFETY SUPERVISOR CONTACTED I E S AND THEY CAME IN AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Ripped or Torn
column168: ON SEPTEMBER 6, 2001 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00AM, I LEFT THE OFFICE IN NORRISTOWN, TO PERFORM ROUTINE WASTE PICK UP OPERATIONS.  MY FIRST STOP WAS IN LANCASTER, PA WHERE I LOADED MANNHEIM SCHOOL DISTRICT (SEE ATTACHED MANIFEST), FIVE PIECES VARIOUS HAZARD CLASSES.  MY SECOND STOP WAS SYNTHES, USA, IN WEST CHESTER, PA WHERE I LOADED SEVEN DRUMS OF CLASS 8 AND THREE NON-HAZARDOUS DRUMS.  MY THIRD STOP WAS CHESTER COUNTY FURNITURE REFINISHING ALSO LOCATED IN WEST CHESTER, PA ABOUT 2 MILES AWAY WHERE I LOADED ONE 30-GALLON DRUM OF CLASS 3 MATERIAL.  ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING.  INSPECTION INCLUDED CONTAINER INTEGRITY, PROPER LABELS AND PROPER CLOSURES.  ALL DRUMS WERE ACCEPTABLE AT TIME OF LOADING.  AFTER LOADING THESE THREE STOPS, I WAS PROCEEDING TO MY FINAL DESTINATION, EEI IN ROYERSFORD, PA WHERE I WAS TO DELIVER THE SEVEN DRUMS FROM SYNTHES.  AT APPROXIMATELY 13:15 I STOPPED TO FUEL MY VEHICLE AT DELCHESTER OIL 304 TURNER ROAD WEST CHESTER PA.  DURING FUELING OPERATIONS, I COMPLETED A BASIC WALK AROUND INSPECTION OF MY TRUCK.  EVERYTHING APPEARED TO BE IN ORDER.  WHILE SECURING THE CAP ON MY FUEL TANK I HEARD A "POPPING" AND "HISSING".  I BACKED AWAY FROM THE VEHICLE TO VISUALLY INSPECT AGAIN.  WITHIN 3-4 SECONDS OF THE SOUND LIQUID STARTED LEAKING OUT OF BOTH FRONT CORNERS OF THE CARGO PORTION OF THE VEHICLE.  THE MATERIAL HAD AN ACIDIC SMELL.  I IMMEDIATELY ENTERED THE CAB OF THE TRUCK TO SECURE MY MANIFESTS, CELL PHONE AND CONTINGENCY PLAN.  I THEY FOLLOWED THE FOLLOWING STEPS:  1- MADE SURE THERE WAS NO ONE IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. THERE WAS NO ONE. 2- VISUALLY OBSERVE THE SPILL AREA LOOKING FOR DRAINS, WATERWAYS OR OTHER SENSITIVE AREA.  NONE EXISTED.  3- CALLED 911 AND NOTIFIED THE DISPATCHER THAT THERE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY.  4- CALLED HAZMAT ONE TO NOTIFY THEM AND HAVE THEM DISPATCH OUR EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR.  5- NOTIFIED THE EMPLOYEES OF DELCHESTER OIL OF THE EMERGENCY. 6- ATTEMPTED TO IDENTIFY THE MATERIAL.  VISUALLY AND WITH PAPERWORK REVIEW. 7- ASSISTED RESPONDING PERSONNEL AS REQUESTED.  8- CONTACTED MARK WEBER. FIRST TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE WAS CORPORAL HOLLAND OF THE WEST GOSHER TWP. POLICE AND A LOCAL EMT TEAM.  UPON CONTACT WITH CORPORAL HOLLAND WE NOTICED SMALL RELEASE OF YELLOW/GREEN VAPOR WAS BEING RELEASED FROM THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE ROAD WAS CLOSED AND THE SCENE WAS ISOLATED.  NEXT TO RESPOND WAS TOM GLASS AND THE CHESTER COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM AS WELL AS LOCAL FIRE PERSONNEL.  THE CHESTER COUNTY TEAM SET UP A DECONTAMINATION UNIT AND PREPARED TO ENTER THE HOT ZONE AND EVALUATE THE MATERIAL AND THE TRUCK.  I PROVIDED A DIAGRAM OF THE INSIDE OF THE CARGO PORTION OF THE TRUCK INCLUDING LOCATIONS OF ALL DRUMS AND THEIR CORRESPONDING HAZARD CLASSES.  I ORIGINALLY THOUGHT THE MATERIAL WAS NITRIC ACID.  THE CHESTER COUNTY HAZ MAT TEAM WORE OSHA LEVEL A PPE, ENTERED THE HOT ZONE, EVALUATED THE SCENE, VERIFIED IT WAS AN ACID WITH A PH TEST STRIP.  THEY OPENED THE BACK OF THE TRUCK,

DURING THE UNLOADING PHASE OF TRAILER, CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. FURTHER INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT CONTAINER HAS A SMALL PUNCTURE ON SIDE. PRODUCT WAS PUNCTURED BY IMPROPER LOADING OF OTHER FREIGHT. MITIGATION OF SPILLAGE WAS MADE AND CONTAINED TO IMMEDIATE AREA OF CONTAINER ON TRAILER FLOOR.

column168: THIS WAS A DIESEL AUTOMOBILE FUEL TANK THAT WAS WRAPPED IN BUBBLE WRAP AND PLACED IN A SEALED/TAPED GARBAGE BAG. IT APPEARS THAT THE CAP/TOP/SEAL FAILED AND THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT MATERIAL IN THIS PACKAGE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP POLICIES.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED ABOUT THIS LEAK AND SAID THAT THERE WAS NOT AN MSDS AVAILABLE FOR THIS FUEL AND THAT THE TANK WAS EMPTY.  SINCE THERE WAS A DIESEL FUEL ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE AND THE SPILL, I WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS. I, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE FAA ABOUT THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER PACKAGING.  ALSO, THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK OFFERED TO FEDEX FOR THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS PACKAGE WILL BE HELD AT THE FEDEX GDMA STATION PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE OCCURRED. THE PACKAGES WERE BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLERS NOTICED LEAKAGE COMING FROM SEVEN PACKAGES.  THE PACKAGES WERE ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL LEAKAGE FROM THE ALUMINUM CANS INSIDE.  THIRTEEN CAN IN TOTAL WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THEIR LIDS.  APPARENTLY THE SEALS FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILLS WERE CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGES WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE SHIPMENTS WERE HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPERS FOR DISPOSITION.

A SALVAGE DRUM WAS USED TO CONTAIN THIS SPILL AND TO PROTECT THIS SHIPMENT WHILE IT IS BEING TRANSPORTED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

A FORKLIFT CAUSED THIS SHRINK-WRAPPED PALLET TO OVERTURN AND CRUSH SEVERAL INNER CONTAINERS.  THIS DAMAGE AND SPILL HAPPENED IN THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER WHERE  A HUB SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THIS SPILL PER FEDEX GUIDELINES.  THIS WILL BE KEPT IN A SAFE LOCATION UNTIL FEDEX RECEIVES PACKAGE DISPOSITION INFORMATION FROM THE SHIPPER.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE/ODOR WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A FUEL PUMP.  THE OUTER PACKAGE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CRUSHED/PUNCTURED BY OTHER PACKAGES AROUND IT.  THE QUALITY OF THE CUSHIONING AND ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS ALSO QUESTIONABLE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT ORIGIN.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL OCCURRED.  APPARENTLY THE ITEM WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING CAUSING THE INNER GLASS PACKAGE TO BREAK AND THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX TO RUPTURE.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO SHIPPER/RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE/ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE UNIT'S CAP SEAL HAD APPARENTLY FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE ITEM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT ORIGIN.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL OCCURRED. THE ITEM WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING. THIS HAD THE EFFECT OF RUPTURING BOTH THE INNER AND OUTER CONTAINERS ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE ITEM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

LATE SATURDAY AFTERNOON A LOUD NOISE WAS HEARD BY FEDEX PERSONNEL AT THE AFORENAMED FACILITY. UPON INSPECTING THE FACILITY THEY FOUND A BOX WITH THE END & SIDE SEAM SPLIT AND PACKAGING MATERIAL DISPERSED. IT APPEARS THE GAS BUILT UP IN THE BOX AFTER BEING RELEASED FROM THE CYLINDER. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AS A MATTER OF PROCEDURE. THE FREIGHT HAS BEEN INSPECTED BY THE FAA & RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

THE SCREW-ON CAP HAD NO POSITIVE CLOSURE. VIBRATIONS IN THE AIRCRAFT & PRESSURES FORCED THE SCREW ON CAP TO BACK IT'S SELF OFF, ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO SPILL. THE SHIPPER FAXED THE MSDS TO REVEAL THE STRENGTH OF THE HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION AT BETWEEN 7%-8%. BOTH 49CFR & ICAO IDENTIFY HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION AS 5% OR GREATER. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I LEFT A MESSAGE FOR SA DON STIGER.
THE BOX WAS DROPPED, CRACKING THE INNER BOTTLE.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL RECOVERED THE SPILL IN THE BOX.  THE DAMAGED BOX WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

THE INNER BOTTLE WAS INTACT.  THERE WAS POSITIVE CLOSURE AROUND THE SCREW-ON CAP.  THE TAPE WAS IN PLACE, BUT ABOUT AN OUNCE OF MATERIAL SNUCK OUT.  THE FREIGHT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED AND CAME DOWN THE BELT WHEN IT WAS NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING.  I PROCEEDED TO REMOVE IT FROM THE BELT WHEN I NOTICED THAT IT WAS EMITTING IRRITATING FUMES, SO I REMOVED IT TO THE OUTDOORS.  I PROCESSED IT THROUGH THE DMP.

WHILE LOADING, CRUDE OIL CAME OUT OF VENT. A HIGH GRAVITY CRUDE OIL CAUSED ADDITIONAL VENTING WHICH CAUSED SOME LIQUID TO CARRY OVER. SPILLAGE WAS BIO-REMEDIATED PER THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT.

column168: DRIVER WAS EXITING REAR GATE OF KINDER MORGAN FACILITY SAN DIEGO AFTER LOADING FOR TOSCO CUSTOMER. ROOT CAUSE: DRIVER ERROR IN JUDGMENT WHILE MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN ON A ROAD WITH A  HIGH CROWN RESULTING IN TRAILER ROLLOVER.  TRAILER WITH 4000 GALLONS REMAINED UPRIGHT. DRIVER CONTACTED COLTON DISPATCHER VIA RADIO IMMEDIATELY AFTER ROLLOVER OF TRAILER.  COLTON DISPATCHER CONTACTED SAN DIEGO POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT(911) AND ALSO INFORMED THE TERMINAL MANAGER AT HOME. COLTON TERMINAL MANAGER CONTACTED SAN DIEGO MANAGER/COMPANY SAFETY SUPERVISOR AND DISPATCHED TO  ACCIDENT SITE. ARRIVED AT SITE 2130 HOURS. HAZMAT TEAM, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL AND TOW TRUCKS(3 AT SITE FOR CLEANUP.  CARGO TANK ACCESS WAS DRILLED AT EACH COMPARTMENT(3) AND REMOVED PRODUCT WITH VACUUM TRUCK, WHICH WAS THAN TRANSFERRED TO A VAN DYK TRUCK AT VAN DYK YARD LOCATED NEAR BY.  WHILE TRAILER WAS ON IT'S SIDE, THERE  WAS ONLY SLIGHT SEEPAGE FROM DOME LIDS. NOT ENOUGH TO LIE REPORTABLE ACCORDING TO HAZMAT TEAM LEADER, NICK VENT. STATEWIDE TOW TRUCK DRIVER JERRY UP RIGHTED TRAILER AND PRODUCT WHICH HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETELY REMOVED FROM TRAILER SPILLED OUT OF DRILLED HOLES WHICH HAD ONLY BEEN DUST TAPED AND NOT PROPERLY PLUGGED BY FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL/FIRE DEPARTMENT. PRODUCT ALSO LEAKED OUT OF THE AREA BETWEEN THE DOUBLE BULKHEAD WHICH HAS A WEEP HOLE WHICH ALSO WAS NOT PLUGGED BEFORE UP RIGHTING TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 1500 POUNDS HAZARDOUS SOLID WASTE REMOVED ON STATE MANIFEST NO. 20203581 TO  D/K ENVIRONMENTAL, 3650 E. 26TH STREET, LOS ANGELES, CA 90023 AND APPROXIMATELY 275 RQ, WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, WATER AND GASOLINE REMOVED ON STATE MANIFEST 20203586 TO DEMENNOKERDOON, 2000 N ALAMEDA, COMPTON, CA.  90222. MANIFEST ATTACHED.  APPROXIMATELY 4800 GALLONS GASOLINE REMOVED FROM ROLLED TRAILER VIA VACUUM TRUCK WAS DELIVERED TO TOSCO LOS ANGELES TERMINAL VIA VAN DYK TRUCK AND RETURNED TO TRANSMIX STORAGE TANK AS A RESULT OF BEING CONTAMINATED BY THE VACUUM TRUCK. VACUUM TRUCK NOT PROPERLY CLEANED PRIOR TO REMOVING PRODUCT FROM ROLLED TRAILER. THE 4000 GALLONS ON THE TRUCK WHICH DID NOT ROLL OVER WAS DELIVERED TO DESIGNATED DELIVERY SITE. ROLLED TRAILER WAS TOWED TO THE COLTON TERMINAL LOCATION AND THAN TO BEALL TRAILERS LOCATED AT 225 W SLOVER AVE, BLOOMINGTON, CA 92316 FOR REPAIRS.

TRAIN CREW NOTICED ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR WHILE DELIVERING TO YARD. YARD MASTER NOTIFIED AND HE CONTACTED CAR INSPECTOR.  THE TASD MANAGER AND ASD SAFETY MANAGER ARRIVE AND CONSULTED WITH THE CARMAN. NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED BUT ODOR COMING FROM CAR. ASD SAFETY MANAGER CALLED THE EMERGENCY CONTACT NUMBER ON THE SHIPPING PAPER-CHEMTREX. CHEMTREX NOTIFIED THE OWNER OF THE CAR,  EQUISTAR CHEMICALS OF CHANNELVIEW, TEXAS. THE RESPONSE TEAM FROM EQUISTAR ARRIVED AT THE ISOLATION SITE AT 1000, 09/03/01.  THEY FOUND VAPOR LEAKING FROM MANWAY GASKET ON LOADING DOME OF CAR.  THE SAID LEAK WAS DUE TO LOOSE BOLTS. THEY APPLIED ANTI-SEIZE COMPOUND TO THE GASKET, TIGHTENED BOLTS AND CHECKED FOR LEAKS.  THEY FOUND NONE.  THEY INSPECTED THE REST OF THE CAR AND FOUND NO OTHER PROBLEMS.  THEY LEFT THE SITE HEADED FOR TEXAS AT 1115 THAT DAY.

BUBBLE OFF TANK HAS A FILTER ON TOP PREVENTING REMAINING ODOR FROM RELEASING INTO AIR. IN THIS CASE THE WATER IN THE TANK WAS AT A 9.5 PH, INDICATING NITROGEN, BUT NOT SATURATED, BUT THE FILTER HAD COLLAPSED ALLOWING AMMONIA ODOR TO VENT TO ATMOSPHERE. UPON CALCULATED ESTIMATES THERE WAS 772 LBS RELEASED. CALCULATIONS ATTACHED.
CENTRAL'S DRIVER UNLOADED AND CUT PUMP OFF AND WHEN DRIVER UNHOOKED HOSES HE DROPPED THE HOSE AND PRODUCT SPILLED.
WHEN UNCOUPLING HOSES STUCK TOGETHER AND DRIVER PULLED APART AND MATERIAL GOT ON GROUND.
CENTRAL'S PUMP LEAKING AT THE PACKING.

DURING THE UNLOADING PHASE OF TRAILER, COMPANY ASSOCIATE WAS ATTEMPTING TO MOVE DRUM WITH DRUM-TRUCK AND PUNCTURED BOTTOM EDGE, CAUSING MINIMAL SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT. SPILLAGE WAS MITIGATED AND CONFINED TO AREA OF DRUM ON TRAILER FLOOR.

column168: DURING INSPECTION BY THE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION (PUC), A TANK CAR CONTAINING FATTY ACID DERIVED FROM COCONUT OIL (OCTANOIC ACID) WAS FOUND TO BE SEEPING AT THE UNLOADING CAP AT THE RATE OF ONE DROP EVERY FIVE MINUTES. THE UNLOADING VALVE WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE IN THE CLOSED POSITION. APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF PINT DRIPPED ONTO A RAILROAD TIE. THE SPILLED OCTANOIC ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH. THE TANK CAR (UTLX 641655) WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED ONTO A SPILL-PROTECTED UNLOADING AREA, AND THE CONTENTS REMOVED. THE CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT, AND SUBSEQUENT CONVERSATIONS WITH THE OES INDICATED NO CONCERN ON THEIR PART, AND SATISFACTION THAT THE INCIDENT WAS HANDLED PROPERLY. THE TANK CAR WILL BE SENT TO A REPAIR FACILITY TO CORRECT THE LEAKING VALVE.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF CHEMICAL PRODUCT LEAKED FROM TRAILER COMPARTMENT DUE TO OPEN VALVES ON TRAILER.  THE TANK INTERNAL VALVE WAS NOT SEATED PROPERLY DUE TO SOME UNKNOWN RESTRICTION.  THE QRV VALVE CAME OPEN IN TRANSIT DUE TO VIBRATION RESULTING IN CHEMICAL LEAKAGE INTO PUMP COMPARTMENT BASIN.  WHEN TRAILER WAS ASCENDING BRIDGES CHEMICAL IN PUMP COMPARTMENT THAT HAD ACCUMULATED SPILLED ONTO ROAD. column168: A FORK BLADE HAD PUNCTURED A HOLE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF ONE PAIL THAT WAS LOADED ON A SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET OF 20 PAILS.  THE PAILS WAS LOCATED ON THE BOTTOM ROW OF PAILS.  AT TIME OF DISCOVERY THE PALLET WAS TAKEN OFF THE TRAILER AND PUT ON THE DOCK AND THE LEAKING PAIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE PALLET.  ABSORBENT WAS PUT ON THE AREA OF DOCK AND TRAILER WHERE THE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED.  A DISCUSSION WAS HELD ABOUT PROPERLY LOADING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WITH A FORK LIFT TO KEEP FROM PUNCTURING CONTAINERS AND THE PROPER USE OF POSITION THAT FORKLIFT FORKS ARE TO BE USED IN MOVING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT ARE LOADED ON PALLETS.  ONE DRIVER WAS INJURED BY THIS SPILL.  SOMETHING LEAKING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS BACKED INTO THE DOCK AND THEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS RAISED.  SOME OF THE SUBSTANCE WAS DRIPPING OFF THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER DOOR.  SOMEHOW THE DRIVER CAME IN CONTACT WITH THIS SUBSTANCE - EITHER SOME GOT INTO HIS RIGHT EYE OR HE MAY HAVE RUBBED HIS EYE AFTER COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE SUBSTANCE.  HE RECEIVED MEDICAL ATTENTION AT THE EMERGENCY ROOM AND MISSED 2 DAYS OF WORK.  HE HAS BEEN RELEASED TO WORK WITH NO RESTRICTIONS.

column168: ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED. ONE INNER BOTTLE WAS LEAKING. THE INNER BOTTLE WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY AND THE REMAINING SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

ON SEPTEMBER 10, 2001 AT 5:50 PM APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) QUART OF A 55% NITRIC ACID SOLUTION SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE AT A TRUCK STOP IN WINNEY, TEXAS WHEN A LEAK DEVELOPED AT A GASKET ON THE INTERNAL VALVE OF A VACUUM TRAILER OPERATED BY RESOURCE TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON SPILL PADS AND DRUMMED FOR DISPOSAL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, PROPERTY DAMAGE, OR THREAT TO HUMAN HEALTH OR THE ENVIRONMENT ASSOCIATED WITH THIS DISCHARGE.

VALVES CHECK AT GENERATOR'S SITE- PREPARED FOR TOP LOADING. CLOSED TOP VALVE FOR TRANSPORTATION TO FACILITY. UPON ARRIVING AT FACILITY, A LEAK FROM THE TRAVEL VALVE WAS NOTICED; VALVE WAS CLOSED BUT PARTICULATE PREVENTED TIGHT SEAL. BUCKET PLACED BY LEAK/STREAM; TRICKLE NOTICED ON ENTRANCE WAY PAVEMENT, BUT NONE TO PUBLIC ROAD. (SHARP) TURN INTO FACILITY CAUSED VOLUME SHIFT, THIS LEAKING OUT VALVE. NO REPORTABLE QUANTITIES REACHED (STATE/FEDERAL) THROUGH LOCAL AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED.

column168: HCE DRIVER DEPARTED WITH LOADED TRAILER FROM OCCIDENTAL THE MORNING OF 9/17/01.  HE STATED THAT AT THE TIME HE LEFT, THE TRAILER HELD A VACUUM. HE DROVE APPROXIMATELY 54 MILES INTO GONZALEZ, LOUISIANA AND STOPPED AT THE USA TRUCK STOP FOR BREAKFAST.  AFTER BREAKFAST, AS HE WALKED TOWARD THE TRUCK AND TRAILER, A BYSTANDER APPROACHED HIM NOTICING THE COMPANY NAME ON HIS UNIFORM, INFORMING HIM THAT THE HCE TRAILER WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR MANHOLE COVER.  HCE DRIVER ACCESSED THE SITUATION AND FOUND THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING AND WAS NO LONGER HOLDING A VACUUM.  HE THEN ENGAGED THE PUMP AND PULLED A VACUUM IN EFFORT TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE LEAK DID STOP. THE DRIVER INHALED VAPORS RELEASED FROM THE PUMP EXHAUST. THE HCE DRIVER CALLED OUR PEARLAND, TEXAS TERMINAL AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND MATERIAL NATURE, TO THE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR.  HE STATED THAT HE WAS SHORT OF BREATH, BUT FELT OKAY.  HE WAS ASKED TO REPORT BACK TO THE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR CONCERNING HIS CONDITION AND THE STATUS OF THE SCENE WITHIN 15 MINUTES.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED KEEP PEOPLE AWAY FROM THE SPILL AREA POINTING OUT TO THEM THE DANGER INVOLVED WHILE THE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR MADE REPORTS TO AUTHORITIES AND ALL OTHER PARTIES CONCERNED.  OCCIDENTAL EMERGENCY CENTER, STATE AND LOCAL PARISH HAZMAT EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND SAFETY KLEEN/ DEER PARK, TEXAS WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  THE LOCAL PARISH HAZMAT TEAM, EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL, THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, LOCAL EMERGENCY MEDICAL SERVICES AND OCCIDENTAL OFFICIALS WERE PRESENT AT THE SCENE.  LIQUID FROM THE LEAKING TANK WAS TRANSFERRED ONTO TWO SMALL CARBON STEAL TANKS PROVIDED BY LOVAC THROUGH EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL. THE LEAKING MANHOLE WAS SECURED AND ALL THREE TRAILERS WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO OCCIDENTAL IN HAHNVILLE.  OCCIDENTAL RELIEVED FUMES FROM THE INITIAL TRAILER, THE GASKET FROM THE LEAKING MANHOLE AS WELL AS ALL OTHER GASKETS ON THAT TRAILER WERE THEN REPLACED.  THE LIQUID WAS THEN TRANSFERRED FROM THE TWO SMALL TRAILERS BACK ONTO THE INITIAL TRAILER.  THE LOAD WAS TRANSPORTED BY HCE DOWN TO SAFETY KLEEN/DEER PARK, TEXAS.  THE TWO LOVAC TRAILERS WILL ALSO BE TAKEN TO SAFETY KLEEN/DEER PARK TO BE THOROUGHLY AND PROPERTY EMPTIED.  EMERGENCY MEDICAL SERVICES RENDERED AID AT THE SCENE TO THE HCE DRIVER AND BYSTANDER WHO INHALED VAPORS.  THEY WERE TAKEN FROM THE SCENE TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM FOR OBSERVATION.

column168: TRUCK OVERTURNED IN MEDIAN- RECEIVED A CALL FROM RALEIGH COUNTY 911 CONCERNING A TANKER WRECK ON I-64 NEAR MILE MARKER 130. ALL LANES OF THE INTERSTATE WERE CLOSED DOWN TO ALLOW FIRE DEPARTMENTS TO EXTINGUISH FIRE. ARRIVED ON SCENE TO FIND THAT THE TANKER WAS FULLY ENGULFED IN FLAMES. SPOKE WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WERE INFORMED THAT THE STORM DRAINS WERE FULL OF FUEL. FLAMES WERE SHOOTING FROM THE STORM DRAINS. FIRE HAD ALSO SPREAD TO THE WOODED AREAS NEAR THE SITE. AS THE FIRES WERE EXTINGUISHED CREWS INSPECTED THE DRAINS FOR FUEL. STORM DRAINS WERE PACKED WITH OIL DRY TO ABSORB FREE LIQUIDS AND RESTRICT FLOW OF CONTAMINATED WATER THROUGH THE DRAINS. TWO BIRMS WERE BUILT TO FURTHER RESTRICT FLOW OF CONTAMINATED WATER. INSPECTED THE SADDLE TANK ON THE TRACTOR (ONLY ONE WAS ON THE TRACTOR) A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL WAS FOUND. A SPLIT AT THE CREASE APPROXIMATELY 1/4"3" ALLOWED MOST OF THE FUEL TO LEAK OUT. A PATCH KIT WAS USED TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE AS THE TRACTOR WAS MOVED. DIESEL FUEL AND GASOLINE WERE DETECTED IN AN AREA APPROXIMATELY 45'LONG BY 5' WIDE ON THE EAST BOUND SHOULDER. AFTER THE TRACTOR WAS MOVED S & W WAS ABLE TO REMOVE THE DRAIN PLUG AND CAPTURE APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. AFTER THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED CREWS WERE ABLE TO ACCESS THE LOWER END OF THE STORM DRAIN AND PLACE BOOMS AT THE STORM DRAIN. WEST BOUND TRAFFIC LANES WERE LITTERED WITH FIRE DEBRIS (CONCRETE, GRASS, SOD, ETC. ) FOR APPROXIMATELY 200'. LANES WERE SWEPT IN ORDER TO ALLOW TRAFFIC TO FLOW. CONTACTED LARRY ROBERTSON WITH DEP. MR. ROBERTSON ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND WALKED THE ENTIRE AREA. HE SAID TO NOT FLUSH THE DRAINS WITH WATER. DEP PREFERS TO ALLOW THE NATURAL FLOW OF RAIN WATER TO NATURALLY REMEDIATE AREAS SUCH AS THIS. BOOMS WILL BE LEFT AT THE LOWER END OF THE STORM DRAIN AND MONITORED REGULARLY. S & W SPOKE WITH MR. ARCHIE WOOD WITH WENDELL WHO THEN GAVE A VERBAL OK TO CONTINUE WITH THE CLEANUP ALREADY IN PLACE. SPOKE WITH BILL DORSEY WITH S & T CLAIMS WHO ALSO AGREED THAT S & W SHOULD PROCEED WITH THE CLEANUP. TANKER REMAINS AND OTHER LARGE PIECES OF DEBRIS WERE REMOVED FROM THE MEDIAN. APPROXIMATELY 5 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE EAST BOUND SHOULDER. FURTHER EXCAVATION IN THIS AREA MAY BE NEEDED AT A FUTURE DATE DUE TO GASOLINE STILL BEING DETECTED. CREWS BEGAN REMOVING CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THE MEDIAN. REMOVED APPROXIMATELY 15 TONS OF SOIL FROM THIS AREA AT A DEPTH OF APPROXIMATELY 3" TO 10" IN THE MIDDLE OF THE MEDIAN AND HIGH LEVELS OF GAS WERE STILL BEING DETECTED. RECEIVED PERMISSION FROM MR. JAMES SHANNON TO TEMPORARILY STORE SOIL AT THE BEAVER-GRADVIEW VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT. TWO WENDELL TRANSPORT REPRESENTATIVES ON SITE AGREED THAT THE LEVELS WERE EXTREMELY HIGH. SMALL TEST HOLES WERE DUG TO AN ADDITIONAL 8" AND FREE LIQUIDS WERE STILL BEING NOTED. NOTIFIED MR. DORSEY WITH S & T CLAIMS THAT LARGE AMOUNTS OF SOIL WOULD NEED TO BE REMOVED FROM THIS SITE. MR. DORSEY HAD EXPECTED THIS DUE TO THE LARGE AMOUNT

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE SEAL ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LEAKING DRUM WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A SEVENTY GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: HYDRAZINE, AQUEOUS SOLUTION, WITH NOT MORE THAN 37 PERCENT HYDRAZINE, BY MASS
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE LEAKING FOUR HUNDRED AND FIFTY GALLON ALUMINUM TOTE WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FAULTY GASKET. THE SHIPPER, BAYER CORPORATION, WAS CONTACTED AND SENT A HAZMAT TEAM TO THE TERMINAL. THE HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP AND REPLACED THE GASKET. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TERMINAL BY BAYER CORPORATION. THE TOTE WAS FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ON 09/08/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 1215 HOURS, WHILE CONDUCTING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE CN/IC GEISMAR YARD, GEISMAR, LOUISIANA, A CN/IC SWITCHMAN NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF RAIL TANK CAR GATX 8129 (SULFURIC ACID, SPENT). TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED. CONSIGNEE'S RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT THE 165 LBS. FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. NEW DISC INSTALLED. TANK CAR DECONED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

UPRR NOTIFIED BNSF THAT INBOUND TRAIN CONTAINED A VENTING ARGON CAR.  BNSF & SHIPPER RESPONDERS FOUND THAT THE LIQUID LINE VALVE IN RIGHT SIDE CABINET WAS 1/3 OPEN WITH THE PACKING NUT COMPLETELY LOOSE ON THIS TANK CAR. RESPONDERS CLOSED VALVE & TOOL TIGHTENED PACKING NUT, ELIMINATING RELEASE. TANK CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AT 2000 HRS. MDT, 9/07.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: TRAILER BEING DERAMPED NOTED WITH SUBSTANCE LEAKING FROM WITHIN.  SHIPPER CONTRACTOR FOUND FIVE 5 GALLON PLASTIC PAILS PARTIALLY CRUSHED DUE TO LOAD SHIFT AFTER AN UPPER PALLET SHIFTED CAUSING LOWER PAILS TO FALL OVER WITH PALLET UPON THEM.  CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED DAMAGED PAILS & CLEANED TRAILER. RECOVERY DRUM PLACED BACK INTO THE NOW ADJUSTED LOAD TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND THAT THE LIQUID LINE VALVE FLANGE BOLTS WERE LOOSE (SOME FINGER LOOSE) & THESE WERE TOOL TIGHTENED, ELIMINATING PRODUCT ODOR RELEASE. column168: CITIZEN REPORTED TANK CAR DRIPPING LIQUID FROM CARS BOTTOM.  BNSF RESPONDERS ALONG WITH L.A. COUNTY F.D. WITH HAZMAT TEAM FOUND CAR LEAKING FIVE DROPS PER MINUTE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET'S OPERATING HANDLE SHAFT DUE TO LOOSE PACKING NUT.  BNSF RESPONDER TOOL TIGHTENED LOOSE PACKING NUT, ELIMINATING PRODUCT DRIP BY 1055 HOURS PDT.  SPILLED PRODUCT EVAPORATED. TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED TWICE WITHIN 8 HOURS AFTERWARDS WITH NO ADDITIONAL RELEASE FOUND.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, ONE FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM IN A SHIPMENT OF EIGHT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON THE DOCK.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED, WHICH AFFECTED ADJACENT CARDBOARD AND THE PALLET THE FREIGHT WAS RESTING ON.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF A CRACK TO THE TOP-SIDE OF THE DRUM DUE TO A PACKAGE FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED AMPHOMAG, ABSORBENT PADS, GLOVES, BOOTIES AND SUITS TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, AFFECTED CARDBOARD AND AFFECTED PACKAGING WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE FAILED FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM.  THE THIRTY AND TEN GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS UNDAMAGED AND IS BEING FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING, ONE LEAKING, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT,  CAUSING A CREASE IN THE DRUM.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, A MASK AND AN ABSORBENT PAD.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PATCHED WITH PUTTY, PLACED INTO A EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING, ONE DAMAGED ONE HUNDRED AND FIFTY-FIVE POUND METAL CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED INTO THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CEMENT YARD.  THE DAMAGE OCCURRED WHEN THE CYLINDER HIT A DOCK BAR AND THE VALVE BROKE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM CONTAINED THE RELEASE IN THE YARD WITH BOOMS AND ABSORBENT AND PERFORMED THE CLEANUP OF THE TRAILER USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG..  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DAMAGED CYLINDER WERE PLACED INTO THE TERMINAL'S WASTE RECEPTACLE.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIVE HUNDRED GALLON STEEL TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASED WAS DUE TO AN OPEN VALVE. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE OPEN VALVE ON THE LEAKING TOTE WAS CLOSED. THE TOTE WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. APPROXIMATELY TWENTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, BOOMS, AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WITH REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A ONE HUNDRED AND TEN GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIVE HUNDRED GALLON STEEL TOTE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE FOURTH QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND AFFECTED THE SURROUNDING DUNNAGE. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO THREE, FORTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TOTE WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: A SMALL OUTAGE OCCURRED WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column168: APPEARS THAT THERE WAS NO BLOCKING AND IN TRANSIT THE BAGS SLIPPED FROM THE PALLET AND FELL ON THE FLOOR RUPTURING SEVERAL BAGS.

THE SHIPPER PLACED THE TOTE ON TRAILER WITH NO AIR VENT IN THE CENTER PART OF THE FILLING CAP. AS THE TRUCK MOVED THE SLOSH OF THE LIQUID SPRAYED OUT AND RAN DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TOTE TANK. THIS WAS A SHIPPERS PACKAGING FAILURE. THEY FAILED TO PROPERLY CONTAIN THE LIQUID FOR TRANSPORTATION. WE PLACED AN AIR VENT IN THE CAP AS IT SHOULD BE AND SHIPPED THE TOTE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.
BARREL TRUCK PIERCED BOTTOM OF DRUM WHEN ROLLING OVER DOCK PLATE, ABOUT 1/2 GALLON LEAKED OUT ONTO FLOOR.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMER LOCATION AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO THE PROPER UNLOADING SITE. THE DRIVER WAS SHOWN WHERE HE WAS TO MAKE HIS CONNECTION AND STARTED THE UNLOADING PROCESS. THE CARGO TANK WAS JUST ABOUT EMPTY WHEN THE CUSTOMER UNLOADING LINE AT THE FITTING CRACKED AND CAUSE ABOUT 5 GALS. SPILL BEFORE THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO SHUT THE VALVES OFF ON THE TRAILER. THE CUSTOMER REPAIRED THE LINE AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND THE DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE ENROUTE THE TOWN OF JUPITER THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT AROUND THE FLANGE OF THE DISCHARGE VALVE IT APPEARED WET. THE DRIVER CHECKED THE VALVE AND FLANGE AND NOTICED THAT THE FLANGE WAS LEAKING AROUND THE GASKET.  THE DRIVER THEN PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK AND NOTIFIED DISPATCH AND THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT OF THE PROBLEM. CTL DISPATCHED TWO MECHANICS TO THE LOCATION OF THE TRAILER AND DISPATCH ANOTHER  CARGO TANK AND DRIVER TO THE LOCATION IN THE EVENT THE LOAD NEEDED TO BE TRANSFERRED CURRA EMERGENCY SERVICE WAS CONTACTED TO MANAGE THE CLEAN-UP FOR CTL. THE DEP WAS CONTACTED AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. CLIFF BERRY ENVORIMENTAL  WAS CONTACTED BY CURRA TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP.  THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE OTHER CARGO TANK WITHOUT INCIDENT AND THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: TOP OF 2 DRUMS NOT TIGHTENED PROPERLY FROM SHIPPER, CAUSING VERY SLIGHT SPILLAGE.  THERE WAS ONLY RESIDUE AFTER HITTING AIR. CALLED SHIPPER EMERGENCY, THEY SENT SOMEBODY TO TIGHTEN THE BUNGS, AND DISPOSE OF RESIDUE. LESS THAN 1 OZ CAME FROM HOLES.

CSX TRANSPORTATION CAR INSPECTORS AT ROUGEMERE YARD FOUND TANK CAR, PROX 30336  TO BE EMITTING AN ODOR. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. AN OUTSIDE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL, RESPONDED. YOUNG'S FOUND THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE PLUG TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND THE VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN. YOUNG'S CLOSED THE VALVE & TIGHTENED THE PLUG. THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.

CSX TRANSPORTATION YARD CREW AT GREENWOOD, SC  SWITCHING TANK CAR ACFX 85692 SMELLED AN ODOR FROM TANK. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. SHIPPER RESPONDED HEPACO TO INVESTIGATE AND HANDLE.  HEPACO FOUND THE PRESSURE PLATE GASKET TO BE OUT OF ALIGNMENT.  DUE TO THE AGE OF THE CAR (3/71) IT WAS DECIDED NOT TO HAVE THE BOLTS TIGHTENED BY AIR GUN. PETRO CLEAN RESPONDED ON BEHALF OF THE SHIPPER TO TRANSFER THE LOAD INTO T/C UTLX 920221 WHICH WAS COMPLETED WITH OUT MISHAP.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: THE TRAIN CREW AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN ROCKDALE, IL REPORTED ACFX 73140, LOAD OF GASOLINE, WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER AUTHORIZED CSXT TO RESPOND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN ABOUT 1/4 TURN.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT AND THE OUTLET VALVE CAP WERE TIGHT.  THE CONTRACTOR CLOSED THE VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO  THE CONSIGNEE.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DISCUSSED WITH THE SHIPPER AND IT WAS ADVISED THAT THE PACKING AROUND THE OPERATING ROD AND THE GASKET IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP BE REPLACED.

NATX 37124, LOAD ACETONE, WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S WEAVERLY YARD IN HOLLAND, MI.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER AUTHORIZED CSXT TO RESPOND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND A 11/2 INCH LENGTH OF PIPE HAD BEEN PLACED OVER ONE OF THE SWING BOLTS AT THE FROM OF THE MANWAY.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE PIPE AND BOLTED IN DOWN BUT DID NOT MAKE A SEAL WITH THE GASKET.  THE CONTRACTOR REMOVED THE PIECE OF PIPE AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER BUT COULD DETECT A PRODUCT ODOR. PRODUCT VAPORS WERE FOUND TO BE COMING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE VAPOR LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED SO THE CONTRACTOR REMOVED THE VALVE, REPLACING IT WITH A PLUG.  WHEN THE VALVE WAS REMOVED IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT HALF OF THE VALVE GASKET WAS MISSING.  THE CAR THEN RELEASED TO BE SWITCHED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DEFICIENCIES WERE DISCUSSED WITH THE SHIPPER WHO INDICATED THEY WOULD FOLLOWUP.

THE CAR INSPECTORS AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD  IN AVON, IN REPORTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM AROUND TANK CAR UTLX 200857, LOAD OF DIETHYL KETONE.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE CAR AND COULD NOT DISCERN ANY SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  ONE OF CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SENTINELS WAS CALLED TO CHECK THE CAR.  HE FOUND THAT 2 OF 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LESS THAN HAND TIGHT. HE SECURED ALL THE MANWAY BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT AND THE ODOR STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: TANK CAR ACFX73139 WAS FOUND BY YARD EMPLOYEES WITH PRODUCT DIPPING OUT OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AREA. CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER BILL GLEASON AND GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES(NEW ORLEANS, LA) RESPONDED,. INSPECTION REVEALS THAT TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT (1/2 TURN LOOSE) AND STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND NOT PROPERLY SECURED (4 TURNS LOOSE). ONE QUART OF PRODUCT LOST. CHEMTREC REPORT#09202001053. PACKING GLAND AND BOTTOM OUTLET  CAP EXCEPTIONS CORRECTED AND CAR SENT TO DESTINATION.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: YARD CREW REPORTS "FUMES AND CLOUD" FROM RAILCAR WHILE IN MOTION. CHEMTREC NOTIFIED (REPORT #09232001003). YOUNGS ENVIRONMENTAL, GRAND RAPIDS, MICHIGAN CONTACTED TO RESPOND.  INSPECTION REVEALS THE FOLLOWING:1) LIQUID LINE RISER PIPE WITH DETERIORATED GASKET AND LOOSE SECUREMENT BOLT; AND 2) NUPRO VALVE SECUREMENT BOLTS LOOSE. CAR ISOLATED UNTIL PROPER GASKET AND BOLTS COULD BE OBTAINED. REPAIRS COMPLETED ON 9/24 WITH COMPATIBLE HMP GASKET MATERIAL AND CARBON STEEL BOLTS. DUPONT REPRESENTATIVE BARRY LINDLEY INFORMED. CAR FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

A TRAILER WAS BEING OFFLOADED AT A SAFETY-KLEEN PROCESSING CENTER WHEN THEY DISCOVERED A LEAKING FIVE GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER OF WASTE ORGANIC CYANIDE. THE LEAK RELEASED APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON OF PRODUCT ONTO THE TRUCK BED. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK WITH THE ORIGINAL LEAKING CONTAINER. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY SEVEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TREATED AND DISPOSED AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 11600 N. APTUS ROAD IN ARAGONITE, UT. THE DIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A WAREHOUSEMAN WAS UNLOADING PALLETS FROM A TRUCK AT THE 10 DAY STORAGE FACILITY WHEN A 16 GALLON METAL DRUM FELL FROM A PALLET ONTO THE TRUCK BED. THE BUNG CAME OFF UPON IMPACT SPILLING OUT EIGHT GALLONS OF PHOSPHORIC ACID ONTO THE TRUCK BED. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH VERMICULITE AND PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK WITH THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY ONE HUNDRED POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1021 BERRYESSA ROAD, IN SAN JOSE, CA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

CARRIER HAS CONSULTED WITH SHIPPER REGARDING ADDITIONAL PRECAUTIONS WITH FITTINGS, REQUESTED STRAPPING FOR FITTINGS. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY POUND PAPER BAG WAS DISCOVERED AT THE THREE-QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER. column168: CARRIER'S DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO ACCESS FREIGHT HE WAS PERPARING TO DELIVER AT AN INTERMEDITATE STOP. WHEN HE DID SO HE FOUND LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE LIQUID STARTED LEAKING OUT OF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. UTILIZING MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT, THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL THE IN THE TRAILER. HE WAS UNABLE TO PINPOINT WHICH DRUM WAS LEAKING OR WHAT DAMAGE HAD BEEN DONE. HE BELIEVED THE PRODUCT WAS FROM A DRUM OF H/M THAT WAS SHRINK WRAPPED TO A PALLET AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THE SHRINK WRAP WAS INTACT AND NOT DAMAGED, BUT THE SPILL WAS MORE DENSE IN THAT AREA. THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN ADVISED THE DRIVER TO EXIT THE VEHICLE AND TO CONFINE HIS EFFORTS TO PREVENT THE MATERIAL FROM SPREADING. PRIOR TO EXITING THE TRAILER THE DRIVER TOOK NOTE OF ONE PLASTIC DRUM THAT APPEARED TO BE UNDER A VACUUM. CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR HANDLE THE SITUATION INSIDE THE VEHICLE. THE CONTRACTOR WAS INSTRUCTED TO FIND THE DAMAGED DRUM AND SECURE IT FOR TRANSPORTATION. THEY WERE TO CLEAN THE TRAILER FLOOR AS BEST THEY COULD AND REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED DIRT FROM UNDER THE TRAILER. WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AND MADE ENTRY INTO THE VEHICLE THEY WERE CONFIRM THE DRIVER'S IDENTIFICATION OF THE LEAKER. AS IT WAS IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, THEY UNLOADED ALL OF THE FREIGHT. THEY FOUND THAT THE LEAKER HAD BEEN SET ON A NAIL IN THE SHIPPER'S PALLET. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM HAD BEEN LOST. CONTRACTOR SECURED THE DRUM IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THEY DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE GROUND UNDER IT. WHEN ALL OF THE WORK WAS DONE THE VEHICLE WAS ABLE TO CONTINUE ON IT'S WAY.

AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP THE DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAKAGE FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM. HE WAS ABLE TO SECURE THE DRUM FROM FURTHER LEAKAGE SO THAT HE COULD CONTINUE HIS DELIVERIES. DRIVER NOTES THAT HE MAKES IT A POINT TO CLOSELY OBSERVE FORK LIFT OPERATORS AS THEY LOAD AND UNLOAD TO PREVENT INADVERTENT FORK LIFT DAMAGE. HE STATES THAT THIS DRUM WAS NOT DAMAGED BY ANYONE SINCE HE LEFT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY WITH IT. WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE THEY CONSULTED WITH THE SHIPPER AND DECIDED TO REFUSE THE DAMAGED DRUM. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL ASSISTED THE DRIVER TO GET THE DRUM TURNED UPSIDE DOWN AND ADDITIONALLY SECURED FOR RETURN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY. IT WAS HELD THERE TO AWAIT SHIPPER'S  INSTRUCTIONS.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 24, 2001, THE TRUCK DRIVER PICKED UP A LOAD OF FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION FROM THE WASTE ACID STORAGE TANK FARM. UPON COMPLETION OF LOADING, THE DRIVER WEIGHED HIS VEHICLE AND LOAD AT THE US STEEL TRUCK SCALE AND FOUND THAT HE WAS ABOVE HIS LEGAL WEIGHT LIMIT FOR THE PUBLIC ROADS. TO REDUCE THE WEIGHT OF HIS LOAD, THE DRIVER MOVED HIS VEHICLE TO AN OFFLOADING STATION. ONCE AT THE OFFLOADING STATION, THE DRIVER CONNECTED ONE END OF A FLEXIBLE HOSE TO A DRAINAGE VALVE ON HIS TRUCK. AFTER ATTACHING THE FLEXIBLE HOSE TO HIS TRUCK, THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRUCK'S DRAINAGE VALVE. THE OTHER END OF THE FLEXIBLE HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO AN OFFLOADING STANDPIPE. THE DRIVER DID NOT PHYSICALLY CHECK THE STANDPIPE CONNECTION PRIOR TO OPENING THE TRUCK'S DISCHARGE VALVE.  A POOR CONNECTION AT THE STANDPIPE RESULTED IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION ONTO THE GROUND SURROUNDING THE STANDPIPE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED PLANT PROTECTION. PLANT PROTECTION FORCES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND APPLIED CAUSTIC TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID. THE POOLED RESIDUAL MATERIAL ALONG WITH STAINED SOIL AND ROCKS WERE PROMPTLY RECOVERED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED. TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN, THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE FOR OVERWEIGHT VEHICLES HAD BEEN CHANGED IN EVENT THAT A DRIVER OVERFILLS HIS TRUCK, HE MUST NOW OFFLOAD HIS TRUCK AT THE FRESH ACID STORAGE FACILITY. THIS FRESH ACID STORAGE FACILITY HAS CONTAINMENT TO PREVENT THE RELEASE OF FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION IN THE EVENT OF A SPILL. THE ISSUE OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST REQUIRES SOME CLARIFICATION. AT THE IRVIN PLANT, THE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION FROM THE CARBON STEEL PICKLING OPERATIONS IS TRANSPORTED TO THE AMROX REGENERATION FACILITY IN ALLENPORT, PENNSYLVANIA. AT THIS AMROX REGENERATION FACILITY, THE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION IS CONVERTED INTO 18% HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND IRON FINES. THE IRON FINES ARE SOLD AS A RAW MATERIAL TO VARIOUS MANUFACTURES WHILE THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID IS RETURNED BACK TO THE IRVIN PLANT FOR USE IN THE PICKLING. SINCE THE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION GENERATED AT THE IRVIN PLANT IS USED AS A RAW MATERIAL FEEDSTOCK TO THE AMROX FACILITY, THE STATE OF PENNSYLVANIA DEFINES THIS MATERIAL AS A  CO-PRODUCT AND  DOES NOT CONSIDER IT AS A WASTE. AS SUCH, THERE IS NO HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST ASSOCIATED WITH THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION. IF THE FERROUS CHLORIDE SOLUTION IS SPILT, AS IT WAS ON THIS OCCASION, THE SPILT MATERIAL IS TREATED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE MATERIALS RECOVERED DURING CLEANUP WERE DISPOSED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THIRTY CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING TEN, ONE QUART PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIRTEEN BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED AND TWO HUNDRED EIGHTY-SEVEN BOTTLES WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY THIRTEEN QUARTS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY THE CARTONS AND SOME DUNNAGE UNDERNEATH THE SKIDS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED CARTONS, AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE THIRTEEN DAMAGED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A SEPARATE FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWO HUNDRED EIGHTY-SEVEN UNAFFECTED BOTTLES WERE REPACKAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL FEDERAL AND STATE REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

A TRUCK OWNED BY ALL STAR TRANSPORTATION, INC WAS BEING LOADED WITH FERROUS SULFATE AT THE ADCOM WIRE COMPANY FACILITY.  WHILE LOADING THE TRUCK WITH FERROUS SULFATE THE HOSE CLAMPS LOOSENED CAUSING THE HOSE TO RELEASE AND FALL ONTO THE SPILL CONTAINMENT AREA IN THE CONTAINED LOADING AREA BEFORE THE OPERATOR COULD SHUT THE PUMP OFF.  AN AMOUNT, UNDETERMINED, AT THE TIME OF THE REPORT TO THE NRC (NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER), EXITED THE CONTAINMENT ONTO THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY OF THE FACILITY AND WAS FURTHER CONTAINED BY PLANT PERSONNEL USING CONTAINMENT AND NEUTRALIZING MATERIALS.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) WAS CONTACTED. UPON DETERMINING THAT THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL RELEASED WAS BELOW THE RQ THE NRC WAS AGAIN CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THAT DETERMINATION.  THERE WAS NO OFF-SITE RELEASE OR PUBLIC HIGHWAY AFFECTED.  NEW LOADING PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN IMPLEMENTED REQUIRING ADCOM EMPLOYEE OVERSIGHT DURING A TRUCK LOADING.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: PETROCHEM RECOVERY SERVICES, INC. (PCRS) PERSONNEL RESPONDED AS REQUESTED AND UPON ARRIVAL ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1630, MET WITH NORFOLK SOUTHERN CORP AND NFD PERSONNEL ON SCENE TO DETERMINE EXTENT OF SPILLAGE AND ACTIONS TAKEN.  IT APPEARED THAT THE SPILLED GASOLINE HAD MIGRATED DURING RAINFALL OVER AN AREA ADJACENT TO THE ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANK (AST) THAT WAS RECEIVING THE DELIVERY TO A STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN THAT IS PART OF THE FACILITY DRAIN SYSTEM THAT DISCHARGES INTO A LARGE RETENTION POND PRIOR TO THE ELIZABETH RIVER.  SORBENT MATERIALS HAD BEEN PLACED AROUND THE CATCH BASIN BY NORFOLK SOUTHERN CORP. AND DOMESTIC INDUSTRIES PERSONNEL WHICH REDUCED THE AMOUNT OF GASOLINE THAT ENTERED THE CATCH BASIN.  THE RETENTION POND WAS CHECKED FOR ANY EVIDENCE OF GASOLINE CONTAMINATION AND NONE WAS FOUND.  THE NEXT CATCH BASIN DOWNSTREAM FROM THE IMPACTED BASIN WAS OPENED AND A SORBENT BOOM WAS DEPLOYED TO CONTAIN ALL CONTAMINATION BETWEEN THE TWO (2) CATCH BASINS.  A PCRS VACUUM TRUCK WAS SET UP TO RECOVER FREE PRODUCT (GASOLINE) AND CONTAMINATED WATER FROM THE SECOND CATCH BASIN WHILE THE PIPING WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER FROM A NFD ENGINE COMPANY.  ADDITIONAL PCRS PERSONNEL RECOVERED ALL FREE STANDING PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AROUND THE AST WITH SORBENT MATERIALS.  A TOTAL OF 544 GALLONS OF GASOLINE CONTAMINATED WATER AND THREE (3) 55 GALLON DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED SORBENT MATERIALS WERE RECOVERED FOR PROCESSING AND PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE SORBENT BOOM IN THE SECOND CATCH BASIN AND THE SORBENT BOOMS SURROUNDING THE FIRST CATCH BASIN WERE LEFT IN PLACE AS A PRECAUTION UNTIL CONTAMINATED SOIL/STONE REMOVAL ACTIVITIES COULD BE SCHEDULED.  ON 9/21/01, PCRS PERSONNEL EXCAVATED 10.91 TONS OF GASOLINE CONTAMINATED SOILS AND STONE FROM AREA ADJACENT TO THE AST TO A MAXIMUM DEPTH OF 4" BELOW GROUND SURFACE FOR THERMAL RECLAMATION AT SOILEX CORP. LOCATED IN VIRGINIA BEACH, VA. FIELD READINGS OBTAINED WITH A PHOTOIONIZATION DETECTOR (PID) SHOWED REMAINING HYDROCARBON LEVELS RANGING FROM 0.1-1.6 PARTS PER MILLION (PPM). BASED ON THESE READINGS AND NO EVIDENCE OF ADDITIONAL SUBSURFACE FREE PRODUCT CONTAMINATION, ALL IMPACTED AREAS WERE BACKFILLED TO GRADE WITH CLEAN #57 STONE FURNISHED ON SITE.  ALL REMAINING SORBENT MATERIALS (1 DRUM) WERE REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED TO PCRS FACILITY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. 11. CONCLUSIONS/RECOMMENDATIONS: IT APPEARS THAT ALL RECOVERABLE FREE PRODUCT AND SURFACE/SUBSURFACE CONTAMINATED SOILS HAVE BEEN ADEQUATELY REMOVED WITH NO IMPACT TO THE ELIZABETH RIVER OR GROUNDWATER.  NO FURTHER REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES ARE RECOMMENDED.

column168: UNIT 140 & 242 T -HAULED CLEAN CRUDE OIL TO SHERWOOD TERMINAL, TRUCK AND TANKER WERE TRAVELLING SOUTH ON HWY #8 TOWARDS SHERWOOD CUSTOMS, ROAD WAS VERY ROUGH WITH LARGE POTHOLES IN THE ROAD, WHEN ABOUT 5 MILES SOUTH ON HWY #8 THE LINE BROKE AWAY FROM THE BELLY VALVE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER DIDN'T NOTICE THE BREAK UNTIL HE STOPPED AT CUSTOMS. DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED SPEARING SERVICE LTD. DISPATCH. THE LOAD LINE WAS FIXED TEMPORARY IN ORDER TO TRAVEL TO LOCATION TO UNLOAD AND CLEAN UP WAS IMMEDIATELY DONE. IN THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT, I COULD ONLY ASK THE DRIVER TO TRAVEL A LITTLE SLOWER ACCORDING TO CONDITIONS AND HOPE OUR SASKATCHEWAN GOVERNMENT COULD SPEND A LITTLE MORE TIME AND MAINTENANCE ON OUR HIGHWAYS.

column168: DURING NORMALLY SCHEDULED AUTOMATIC DELIVERY, DRIVER NOTED THAT NO VENT ALARM WAS AUDIBLE DURING FILLING.  DRIVER STOPPED DELIVERING AND CALLED OFFICE TO NOTE POSSIBLE TANK PROBLEM.  OWNER OF PROPERTY CALLED TO REPORT OIL RELEASE IN BASEMENT.  39 GALLONS SPRAYED INTO BASEMENT.  UPON INSPECTION AT TIME OF INCIDENT IT WAS OBSERVED THAT FILL AND VENT LINE WERE DISCONNECTED FROM TANK.  OWNER OF THE PROPERTY REPORTED THAT HE HAD DISCONNECTED THE LINES TO MOVE THE TANK. column168: A NON-DOT SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK DEVELOPED A LEAK WHEN A 3/8-INCH "SAMPLE TESTING LINE" JOINT SEPARATED CAUSING ARGON TO RELEASE LIQUID ARGON TO THE ATMOSPHERE INSIDE THE OPERATING COMPARTMENT AT THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK. THE CARGO TANK WAS REMOVED TO A "SAFE ZONE" BEHIND THE TOLL PLAZA WHERE THE LEAK WAS CAPPED AFTER PRAXAIR WAS NOTIFIED OF THE LEAK.  AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE REVEALED THAT THE LIQUID ARGON SAMPLE LINE HAD COME LOOSE AT A COMPRESSION FITTING CAUSING LIQUID ARGON TO VENT TO THE ATMOSPHERE INSIDE THE REAR COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER.

column168: TWO 5 GALLON STEEL CONTAINERS CONTAINING CHEMICAL GROUT (A FLAMMABLE LIQUID MATERIAL) WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING INSIDE OF COMMERCIAL AIR CRAFT INTO DENVER.  PLANE WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE A DANGEROUS SPECIALISTS AND FIRE CREW WAS SENT TO THE AIRCRAFT.  FAA WAS CALLED DOWN TO DENVER AIR CARGO FACILITY TO DO AN INVESTIGATION.  PREVENTIVE ACTION: AFTER 9-11, 100% INSPECTION IS REQUIRED ON CLOSED AND BOTTLED CONTAINERS.  I APOLOGIZE FOR THIS REPORT BEING LOST DUE TO THE EVENTS FOLLOWING 9-11.  THIS FORM IS BEING FILED PURSUANT TO 49CFR PART 175.31.

DRIVER WAS PUMPING OUT DIESEL AT A STATION THAT WAS TO BE REMODELED. EMPTYING TANKS OF PRODUCT TO RETURNING TO TERMINAL. WHILE EMPTYING DIESEL TANK PTO ON TRUCK TO PUMP OUT PRODUCT SEIZED WHICH CAUSED VIOLET VIBRATION WHICH SHOOK HOSE FROM TRUCK CONNECTION DIESEL FLOWED TO GROUND AND DRIVER SHUT OFF IMMEDIATELY. DRIVER DIKED DRAIN TO MAKE SURE NOTHING GOT INTO DRAIN. CREW ARRIVED SHORTLY TO CLEAN UP DIESEL SPILL. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND SPILL MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY TRUCK WAS TAKEN TO SHOP TO REPAIR PTO SYSTEM.

column168: E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 12359. ONE CARTON MEASURING 1 FT. BY 6 IN. HAD BEEN REPORTEDLY CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT AND AS A RESULT LEAKED ITS CONTENTS. THE CARTON CONTAINED ONE 4 LITER PLASTIC CONTAINER OF CORROSIVE LIQUID BASIC, ORGANIC, NOS (ETHANOLAMINE CATECHOL). THE OUTER CARDBOARD BOX WAS COMPLETELY SATURATED WITH PRODUCT, HOWEVER, NO VISIBLE CONTAMINATION TO THE TRAILER FLOOR, OTHER FREIGHT OR OTHER SURFACES WAS VISIBLE OR NOTED. CF EMPLOYEES SIMPLY TOOK THE CARTON AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE AT THE TERMINAL'S DAMAGED FREIGHT AREA FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL AT AN PROPERLY PERMITTED FACILITY.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING DRUMS OF PRODUCT FROM TRAILER AND STRUCK ONE OF THE DRUMS WITH THE FORK CAUSING THE RELEASE. APPROXIMATELY 4 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. TERMINAL PERSONNEL QUICKLY PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS THEN USED TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR. THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A 5-GALLON CONTAINER AND PLACED IN A SECURE AREA PENDING DISPOSAL. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE (E.M.I. JOB #12389). E.M.I. NOTIFIED THE REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER (A. GAY) FOR THE TERMINAL OF THE RELEASE. THERE WAS NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES. THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO ANY STORM DRAINS, WATERWAYS OR SOIL. THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: CROWN VEHICLE, TRACTOR#231200/TANK TRAILER #220321, DRIVEN BY GARY GROVER, WAS HEADING NORTH BOUND ON HIGHWAY 79 WHEN A DEER JUMPED OUT IN FRONT OF THE VEHICLE. THEN DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID THE DEER, LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, AND SUBSEQUENTLY ROLLED THE VEHICLE OVER DIESEL PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE TANK TRAILER COMPARTMENTS AND SUBSEQUENTLY IGNITED. THE VEHICLE TRACTOR AND TRAILER, WAS TOTALLY DESTROYED AND THE ENTIRE CARGO(7601 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL) WAS CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO CULLMAN HOSPITAL AND WAS IN SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED (BROKEN COLLAR BONE). ACTION RESOURCES ( RESPONSE CONTRACTOR) WAS ON SCENE AND REMOVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF SOIL IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE/FIRE. BLOUNTSVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT, ALABAMA DOT PERSONNEL INDICATE A 40'X 28' SECTION OF THE ROADWAY WOULD NEED TO BE RESURFACED. HIGHWAY 79 WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 HOURS. NRC REPORT 579630 WAS FILED.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING GASOLINE (GRAVITY DROP) AT THE CROWN STATION DURING A HEAVY RAINSTORM, APPROXIMATELY 200-300 GALLONS SPILLED FROM THE FILL CONNECTION/SPILL CONTAINMENT BUCKET ONTO THE ASPHALT DRIVE.  SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION BY CROWN INDICATES THAT THE UNDERGROUND REGULAR TANK WAS OVERFILLED (AND GASOLINE SPILLED OUT OF THE SPILL CONTAINMENT BUCKET AND/OR LEAKED FROM THE UNLOADING FITTING/FILL CONNECTION).  INVENTORY RECONCILIATION INDICATES AN APPROXIMATE 200+ GALLON LOSS.  THE DRIVER DID NOT REPORT THE INCIDENT TO THE COMPANY.  THE FORESTDALE FIRE DEPT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AFTER RECEIVING A COMPLAINT ABOUT GASOLINE VAPORS.  UPON NOTIFICATION, CROWN PERSONNEL NOTIFIED NRC (REPORT #578702).  A DEM OFFICIALS WERE ONSITE.  THE INITIAL INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT GASOLINE HAD RUN OFF THE STATION'S ASPHALT LOT, DOWN A GRASSY EMBANKMENT AND INTO STORM DRAINS FEEDING VILLAGE CREEK.  ACTION RESOURCES RESPONDED FOR CROWN. CLEANUP FOCUSED ON REMOVING IMPACTED GRASS/SOIL.  DRIVER WAS SUSPENDED PENDING INVESTIGATION.

THE NAIL WAS PROTRUDING FROM ANOTHER PALLET NEXT TO THE FREIGHT. column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SCAN WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY OCCURRED.  APPARENTLY THE ITEM WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING LEADING TO THE RUPTURE OF INNER PLASTIC UNITS CONTAINING A GERMICIDAL DETERGENT LIQUID.  THIS HAD THE EFFECT OF COMPROMISING THE OUTER PACKAGING.  WHILE THE SPILL WAS BEING CLEANED UP HANDLERS NOTICED THREE AEROSOL CANS IN THE PACKAGE AS WELL.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE QUALIFYING THE AEROSOLS NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION. TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT DANNY WAHL/FAA/LAX/CASFO AT 12:05 (CST) ON 09/05/2001.

REFERENCE TO THE ONLINE MSDS SYSTEM ALSO YIELDED INFO ON THE MATERIAL'S MAKEUP AND DEGREE OF FLAMMABILITY. (FP 120'F. THE FREIGHT WAS CORRALED AND PLACED IN DOCUMENT BAGS. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA IN INDY WAS NOTIFIED. I SPOKE TO SA RALPH ROMAINE. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: A YUASA 12V MOTORCYCLE BATTERY WAS CONFISCATED FROM A PASSENGER (IN CARRY-ON BAGGAGE) DUE TO IATA RESTRICTIONS. BATTERY WAS HELD IN TEMPORARY ACCUMULATION AREA, AWAITING DISPOSAL. DURING TEMPORARY STORAGE. BATTERY ACID (SULFURIC ACID SOLUTION) SPILLED IN THE CABINET AND OUT ONTO AN ADJACENT CARPETED AREA. DAMAGING THE CARPET. THE DAMAGED CARPET WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED. THE CABINET WAS CLEANED. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH REGULATIONS REGARDING HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL. THE BATTERY WAS NOT DAMAGED. THE SPILL APPARENTLY OCCURRED FROM A LOOSE FITTING CAP ON ONE OF THE BATTERY CELL FILL PORTS.
column172: Packages or containers checked on board an aircraft by a passenger in addition to luggage

column168: WHILE LOADING BAGS IN FLIGHT 723 TO GYE, EMPLOYEES SENSED A STRONG SMELL COMING FROM CANVAS BAG BELONGING TO PASSENGER ELVY ORTIZ. PASSENGER WAS QUESTIONED AND IDENTIFIED PRODUCTS. PASSENGER HAD A TOTAL OF 3 SOFT SIDED BAGS ALL IDENTICAL IN MATERIAL AND MANUFACTURING. ALL 3 BAGS HAD SMALLER PLASTIC CONTAINERS APPROXIMATELY 1 CUBIC FEET EACH. INSIDE THESE PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE VARIOUS GLASS AND PLASTIC BOTTLES CONTAINING VARIOUS LIQUIDS FOR MANICURE PURPOSES. IN ONE BAG, INSIDE A PLASTIC CONTAINER, TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES OF .5 OZ EACH HAD THE CAPS POPPED OFF AND ONE GLASS BOTTLE OF 1.5 OZ BROKE. IN THE OTHER BAG, INSIDE A PLASTIC CONTAINER, ONE GLASS BOTTLE OF 1 OZ BROKE. THE SPILLED LIQUIDS WERE CONTAINED BY THE PASSENGER CLOTHING AND BY TOWELS PLACED INSIDE THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS. NO LIQUID SPILLED OUTSIDE THE PLASTIC CONTAINER OR THE CANVAS BAGS. TWO OUT OF THREE BAGS HAD BEEN LOADED IN THE AIRCRAFT, ONE WAS NOT. THE FLIGHT TOOK AN 18 MINUTES DELAY SEARCHING AND UNLOADING THE TWO BAG.

column168: WHILE LOADING BAGS IN FLIGHT 723 TO GYE, EMPLOYEES SENSED A STRONG SMELL COMING FROM CANVAS BAG BELONGING TO PASSENGER ELVY ORTIZ. PASSENGER WAS QUESTIONED AND IDENTIFIED PRODUCTS. PASSENGER HAD A TOTAL OF 3 SOFT SIDED BAGS ALL IDENTICAL IN MATERIAL AND MANUFACTURING. ALL 3 BAGS HAD SMALLER PLASTIC CONTAINERS APPROXIMATELY 1 CUBIC FEET EACH. INSIDE THESE PLASTIC CONTAINERS WERE VARIOUS GLASS AND PLASTIC BOTTLES CONTAINING VARIOUS LIQUIDS FOR MANICURE PURPOSES. IN ONE BAG, INSIDE A PLASTIC CONTAINER, TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES OF .5 OZ EACH HAD THE CAPS POPPED OFF AND ONE GLASS BOTTLE OF 1.5 OZ BROKE. IN THE OTHER BAG, INSIDE A PLASTIC CONTAINER, ONE GLASS BOTTLE OF 1 OZ BROKE. THE SPILLED LIQUIDS WERE CONTAINED BY THE PASSENGER CLOTHING AND BY TOWELS PLACED INSIDE THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS. NO LIQUID SPILLED OUTSIDE THE PLASTIC CONTAINER OR THE CANVAS BAGS. TWO OUT OF THREE BAGS HAD BEEN LOADED IN THE AIRCRAFT, ONE WAS NOT. THE FLIGHT TOOK AN 18 MINUTES DELAY SEARCHING AND UNLOADING THE TWO BAG.

column168: ON 09/12/2001 JCI DRIVER RONNIE TORISK WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF 10 55-GALLON DRUMS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TO DUKE POWER IN YORK, SC. TWO-ONE GALLON JUGS WERE PUNCTURED RELEASING THEIR CONTENTS TO THE CONCRETE FLOOR. THE RIVERSIDE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ-MAT TEAM MOBILIZED TO THE SITE ALONG WITH AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WHO OVERPACKED THE LEAKING AND DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND CLEANED UP THE FLOOR. column168: E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 12364 THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH DRUMS ENROUTE TO A DRUM RECYCLING/RECONDITIONING FACILITY WHEN SEVERAL ON THE TOP ROW OF THE DOUBLE STACKED LOAD TIPPED  OVER. ONE DRUM HAD A HOLE IN THE SIDE WHICH ALLOWED 1- 2 GALLONS OF REMAINING PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. A HAZ MAT TEAM WIPED UP THE SPILLAGE WITH RAGS AND PLACED IN A DRUM FOR OFF SITE DISPOSAL.  ALL DRUMS WERE UPRIGHTED.  THE DRUM WHICH HAD THE HOLE IN THE SIDE WAS SECURED SO THAT NO FURTHER SPILLAGE WOULD OCCUR.  THE TRUCK WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TRAVEL TO THE DRUM RECYCLING FACILITY.

IMPROPER LOADING CAUSED RELEASE OF PRODUCT ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

STEVE, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR TIMX 201034 LOCATED IN THE NEFF YARD ON TRACK 307 WAS VENTING FROM THE TOP. MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, CHRIST HORNICK WAS NOTIFIED. MGR HORNICK AND HAZMAT RESPONSE, CONTRACTOR, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND RELIEVED THE PRESSURE ON THE TANKCAR. MRS. HORNICK ADVISED THAT THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE PLATE. column168: DURING TANK CAR INSPECTION, MGR ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, PAUL PERSON, FOUND THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING AT THE LAREDO YARD. HE DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS MISSING AND ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE. THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED ALL BOLTS SECURED. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

AT 0600HRS ON 09-05-01, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT MYO CURT HUCKABY HAD REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 49160 TO BE LEAKING IN TRACK 402, SETTEGAST YARD. THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING AT A CONTINUOUS RATE THE SIZE OF A PENCIL FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. WHILE ENROUTE TO THE SCENE, MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, MERRISOL USA LLC OF HOUSTON, TX AND SPOKE TO SAFETY SUPERVISOR TOM MCWILLE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO DISPATCH A PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, A CHEMIST AND DISPATCH GARNER HAZMAT/ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDERS. INITIAL INSPECTION OF CAR BY MGR LERCH DEVELOPED PRODUCT DRIPPING AT A RATE OF 50 DROPS A MINUTE FROM THE 2 INCH AUXILIARY BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, WITH NO POOLING OF PRODUCT, FURTHER INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE TO BE FROM THE THREADS WHERE THE AUXILIARY VALVE SCREWS INTO THE PRIMARY BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND FROM THE THREADS OF THE 2 INCH PLUG ON THE  AUXILIARY VALVE UPON ARRIVAL OF MERISOL PERSONNEL AND GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL THE AUXILIARY VALVE WAS TIGHTENED 3/4 TURN AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE PLUG 1 TURN. AFTER SECUREMENT OF THE CAR, IT WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION. GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL COMPLETED THE REMEDIATION AND CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILL. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TIM O'BRIEN, REG. MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC OF A REAR END COLLISION INVOLVING TWO TRAINS NEAR JACKSONVILLE, TX. ONE CAR WAS REPORTED ON FIRE O'BRIEN RESPONDED WITH ASSISTANCE FROM MIKE KELLY, MGR CTS AND INSPECTED SITE. THEY FOUND NINE CARS DERAILED WITH NO LEAKS OR SIGNIFICANT SHELL DAMAGE. TANK CAR SCMX 4316 HAD A LARGE HOLE ON THE TOP AND HEAD OF THE A END AND THE PRODUCT (ACETONE) WAS BURNING VIGOROUSLY. THE TANK CAR WAS SLOWLY MOVED TO THE EASTERN MOST CROSSING (APPROX 1/4 MILE) AND ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO PUT THE FIRE OUT. WHEN NOT SUCCESSFUL, THE CAR WAS PLUMBED FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO A LIQUID FLARE PIT CONSTRUCTED NEAR BY. THE LIQUID REMAINING IN THE CAR WAS SUCCESSFULLY FLARED IN THE PIT AND THE TANK CAR COOLED.

NOTIFIED OF SPILL AT 06:25 09/07/2001.  SPILL WAS A BLOOD-LIKE SUBSTANCE SPREAD IN A 2 X 3 FOOT AREA OF THE F2 CARGO HOLD ON AIRCRAFT 2BV.  THE SUBSTANCE WAS DRIED.  WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL OF FRIDLEY, MN ARRIVED AT 09:15 TO CLEAN SPILL.  FIELD TESTS DETERMINED SUBSTANCE TO BE A NEUTRAL PH. column168: AT APPROX 3:15 DRIVER DOUG LYNN CALLED IN- HE WAS ON THE ON RAMP TO I-70 WEST FROM SRI NORTH OF CONNERSVILLE. AS HE HAD TURNED THE CORNER ONTO THE RAMP HE THOUGHT HE COULD SMELL HIS LOAD & STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE. HE FOUND SOLVENT LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OF TANK IN THE AREA BETWEEN COMPT. 1 & 2. AFTER CONSULTING W/ RICK P. & LARRY M IT WAS DECIDED THE BEST COURSE OF ACTION WAS TO OFFLOAD COMPTS 1 & 2 WHERE THE TANKER SAT IF WE COULD. I CALLED THE IND. ST. POLICE C'VILLE POST & TOLD THEM THE SITUATION. THEY SAID THEY WOULD SEND SOMEBODY TO THE SCENE BUT THAT THEY WOULD RATHER WE WENT UP THE ROAD TO THE REST AREA TO DO THE TRANSFER. WHEN I EXPLAINED THAT WE BELIEVED THE LEAK TO BE STRUCTURAL & WE DIDN'T WANT TO MOVE THE TRAILER SHE SAID SHE WOULD HAVE SOMEONE GET BACK TO ME. ABOUT 3:45 FRED BUNZENDAHL OF STATE POLICE MOTOR CARRIER DIV CALLED- TOLD ME HE WAS IN ROUTE TO SCENE & ASKED FOR INFO I FILLED HIM IN & WAS TOLD HE WOULD CALL BACK WHEN HE GOT TO THE SCENE. DURING THIS TIME WE LOCATED TODD BY CELL PHONE & FOUND THAT HE WAS IN ROUTE TO C'VILLE WITH A BOX & WAS ALMOST TO SRI. WE TOLD HIM TO DROP OFF HIS SPILL KIT & PRECEDE QUICKLY TO C'VILLE DROP THE BOX- P/U AN EMPTY TANKER & PLENTY OF HOSES (IN CASE WE NEED TO UNLOAD FROM BEHIND THE TRUCK) & GET BACK TO DOUG TO UNLOAD COMPT 1 & 2. FRED CALLED BACK A LITTLE AFTER 4 (P) WAS AT THE SCENE DOUG HAD SUCCESSFULLY BUILT A DIKE OUT OF THE SPILL KIT THAT WAS CONTAINING EVERYTHING TO FRED'S SATISFACTION FRED ALSO SAW WHERE THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING & AGREED WITH OUR ASSESSMENT THAT IT SHOULD NOT BE MOVED. HE ASKED FOR & RECEIVED ETA FOR TODD (4:45) HE ALSO CLOSED THE RAMP AT 4:00 P. TODD ARRIVED- WAS GIVEN ACCESS- THE PUMP OFF WENT FINE & W/O INCIDENT & SCENE WAS LEFT @ 6:15. BECAUSE OF THE RAMP CLOSURE I CALL (AS ADVISED BY STEVE M.) THE NAT. RESPONSE CENTER @ 4:40 (THE RAMP HAD NOT BEEN CLOSED FOR 1 HOUR YET WHEN THE CALL WAS PLACED) (49 CFR 171.15 A (1) (V). & WAS GIVEN INCIDENT REPORT # 578933 BENNETT. FRED HAD CALLED FOR BACKUP & RECEIVED A STATE POLICE TROOPER, THE CAMBRIDGE CITY & WAYNE CO. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45 PM ON 07 SEP-2001, THE SHIPPING SUPERVISOR WAS ALERTED TO A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE DALLAS SHUTTLE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED AWAY FROM THE BUILDING AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE WOODLANDS FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE FACILITY AND LOCATED A BOX OF XYLENE CHEMICAL THAT WAS OBSERVED TO BE WET. THE BOX WAS UNDAMAGED AND WAS LOCATED ON THE DESIGNATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PALLET.  THE 4 PLASTIC ONE-GALLON CONTAINERS OF XYLENE WERE FOUND TO BE IN THEIR ORIGINAL MANUFACTURER'S BOX. OF THE FOUR 1-GALLON CONTAINERS, ONE WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY HALF OF ITS CONTENTS. LATER EXAMINATION OF THE LEAKING ONE-GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER IDENTIFIED A SMALL PIN-SIZE HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE CONTAINER NEAR THE SEAM AT THE BOTTOM OF THE JUG.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL EVACUATED THE BUILDING AND BACKED THE TRUCK TOT HE FACILITY'S DOCK SO THAT IT COULD BE PROPERLY OFFLOADED IN ORDER TO GAIN BETTER ACCESS TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PALLET. THE BOX OF XYLENE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED AND THE TRAILER AREA WAS ABATED.  THE XYLENE WAS PLACED INTO AN APPROVED HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTAINER AND MOVED TO THE FACILITY'S HAZARDOUS WASTE ACCUMULATION AREA. ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL WILL BE CONTRACTED TO REMOVE AND DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL IN THE NEAR FUTURE.  THE TOTAL TIME FOR ABATING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND ADEQUATELY VENTILATING THE AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO HOURS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES INCURRED FROM THE SPILL, EVACUATION OR ABATEMENT PROCESS.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 20,2001 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 AM OUR BOBTAIL TANK TRUCK ENTERED INTERSTATE HWY 5 @ TELEGRAPH ROAD IN THE CITY OF COMMERCE. HEADING NORTH TOWARD THE ATLANTIC BLVD ON RAMP, THE TRUCK WAS APPARENTLY CUT OFF BY A SECOND VEHICLE. UPON SWERVING TO AVOID COLLIDING WITH THE VEHICLE THE TANK TRUCK WHICH WAS LOADED WITH 4000 GALLONS OF RED DYED DIESEL HIT THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY AND STEERED BACK INTO THE LANES. WHILE ATTEMPTING TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE TRUCK, THE DRIVER OVER CORRECTED THE STEERING WHEEL AND CAUSED THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN, LANDING ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRUCK. THE IMPACT WITH THE GROUND SPLIT TWO WELDS IN THE FRONT COMPARTMENT AND RUPTURED A 12 INCH HOLE IN THE REAR COMPARTMENT.THE CONTENTS OF THE REAR COMPARTMENT (APPROX.800) GALLONS WERE LOST DURING THE INITIAL ACCIDENT AND THE FRONT COMPARTMENT (APPROX. 3200 GALLONS) CONTINUED TO LEAK UNTIL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL PUMPED OUT THE TRUCK INTO A VACUUM TRUCK. IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE ACCIDENT 911 WAS CALLED. ARRIVING ON SCENE WAS THE LA COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT, CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL, CALIFORNIA TRANSIT AUTHORITY, U.S. COAST GUARD, UNITED PUMPING SERVICE, AND J & M TOWING. THE FIRE DEPT. PROCEEDED TO DAM THE SPILL, BLOCK THE STORM DRAIN, AND EVACUATE THE IMMEDIATE AREA. CHP CLOSED THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF THE HWY. UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, UNITED PUMPING VACUUMED THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE FREEWAY AND FROM INSIDE THE TANK TRUCK. J & M TOWING RIGHTED AND REMOVED THE DAMAGED TRUCK. UNDER THE DIRECTION OF CAL TRANS, UNITED PUMPING THEN PUMPED OUT THE SPILLED PRODUCT OUT OF A RESERVOIR UNDER THE FREEWAY. OUT OF THE TOTAL CONTENTS OF THE ORIGINAL LOAD OF 4000 GALLONS, 2800 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED FROM THE FREEWAY AND FROM THE TRUCK AND 4800 GALLONS OF PRODUCT AND WATER WAS RECOVERED FROM THE RESERVOIR FOR A TOTAL OF 7600 GALLONS. THE 2800 GALLONS WHICH WAS SALVAGED FROM THE FREEWAY AND TRUCK IS TO BE SOLD AS TRANMIX FUEL. THE FREEWAY WAS REOPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 3PM ATTACHED ART THE MANIFESTS FOR THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MATERIALS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0030 HRS. 9-18-01 A SPRINGFIELD MA POLICE OFFICER OBSERVED A VAPOR CLOUD AT THE APRIA HEALTHCARE FACILITIES STAND TANK LOCATED AT 170 CARANDO DRIVE, SPRINGFIELD, MA. THE POLICE DISPATCHER CONTACTED THE ON-CALL APRIA PATIENT SERVICE TECHNICIAN, LARRY GORE, WHO IN TURN CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR LEO COLTEY. UPON ARRIVAL COLTEY FOUND THAT THE SPRINGFIELD EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS HAD SECURED THE AREA. COLTEY WAS NOT ALLOWED TO APPROACH THE STAND TANK. HE ADVISED MR. JIM CONTRAVIC WHO APPEARED TO BE IN CHARGE OF THE HAZMAT TEAM THAT THE TANK CONTAINED OXYGEN REFRIGERATED LIQUID AND THAT HE WAS FULLY TRAINED IN ITS OPERATION. CONTRAVIC STILL REFUSED TO LET HIM APPROACH THE TANK. CONTRAVIC ASKED WHERE THEY GOT THEIR OXYGEN AND HE WAS ADVISED THAT THEY PURCHASED IT FROM PRAXAIR AND HAD BEEN SCHEDULED TO RECEIVE A DELIVERY SOMETIME THAT NIGHT. CONTRAVIC DIRECTED COLTEY TO CALL PRAXAIR IMMEDIATELY. PRAXAIR WAS CONTACTED AND THEY ADVISED THAT THEIR AREA MAN WAS OUT OF TOWN FOR TRAINING AND THAT THE NEAREST PERSON WAS JOHN DEPUTAT LOCATED IN TEWKSBURY, MA, APPROXIMATELY 100 MILES AWAY. DEPUTAT ADVISED CONTRAVIC THAT COLTEY WAS FULLY QUALIFIED TO HANDLE THE SITUATION. CONTRAVIC ORDERED DEPUTAT TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. COLTEY THEN CONVINCED THE OFFICIALS THAT BOB IVERSON, IVEY INDUSTRIES, WHICH IS A LOCAL COMPANY THAT SERVICES THE BRANCHES LIQUID VESSELS, WAS QUALIFIED TO ADDRESS THE ISSUE. CONTRAVIC HAD COLTEY CALL IVERSON TO THE SCENE. IT IS OUR UNDERSTANDING THAT, UPON ARRIVAL, IVERSON INSPECTED THE TANK AND FOUND THAT PRAXAIR HAD FILLED THE TANK AT APPROXIMATELY MIDNIGHT. HE ALSO FOUND THAT A VALVE HAD NOT BEEN CLOSED SECURELY. IVERSON SHUT THE VALVE AND THE RELEASE WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED WHILE PRAZAIR BELIEVES ITS PERSONNEL DID NOT LEAVE A VALVE OPEN ON THE TANK, APRIA IS NOT SURE WHICH VALVE WAS SHUT BY IVERSON AND WE DO NOT KNOW WHETHER THAT VALVE WAS LEFT OPEN BY APRIA OR PRAXAIR PERSONNEL. THE AREA REMAINED SECURE UNTIL THE CLOUD HAD DISSIPATED. CONTRAVIC THEN RELEASED THE SCENE AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS LEFT THE SCENE. NO DAMAGE OR INJURIES RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT.

column168: FILE: 2166 F & D, SHIPPER: M B D CONSTRUCTION, AWB BTR 6505277015 AUS.  ON 09/27/2001 AT 0215 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING K OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES AND BETH PARKER DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  THEY WERE ADVISED THAT THIS DID HAVE ON OF THE BELTS DOWN IN THIS AREA.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT HAD OBVIOUS SIGNS OF LEAKAGE COMING FROM THIS PACKAGE.  THEY CONTAINED THE SPILL INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH A UNIVERSAL PAD AND ATTEMPTED TO IDENTIFY THE PRODUCT. INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX THERE WERE 3 x 1 GALLON METAL CANS WITH METAL LIDS.  THESE LIDS DID NOT HAVE POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THEM, WHICH ALLOWED ONE LID TO BECOME LOOSE, CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF ONE OF THESE CANS.  THESE CANS DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THEM.  THIS DID NOT CONTAIN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT AN PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED THE RECOVERY DRUM IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS HAD THE AREA DOWN FOR 110 MINUTES. THEY CLEANED THE BELT WITH "TRIPLE S SOLVENT/DEGREASER".  THE AREA WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED IN THESE EMPLOYEES, AND NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  WE REQUESTED AN MSDS FOR THE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT AND UPON READING THIS MSDS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT HIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  ACCORDING TO THE MSDS THE FLASH POINT IS BELOW 100 F.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE ANY MARKINGS, LABELS, OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  A COPY OF THE MSDS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0410.

column168: AT 10:00 PM I RECEIVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING FLAMMABLE HAZARD MATERIAL USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET I PICK UP THE SPILL WEARING THE PROPER PPE. THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM NO CLEAN  UP WAS NEEDED AT SITE

APPROXIMATELY 7:00 AM A LEAKING FLAMMABLE LIQUID PACKAGE CAME DOWN THE BELT. MARGRET DEOS A PRELOADER HAD JUST COMPLETED GIVING THE ENTIRE BELT CHSP AUDITS. SHE HAD ALSO GIVEN ME A FIRST RESPONDER HAZWOPPER AUDIT AND WAS THEN IN THE PROCESS OF DOING A SAFETY HABITS AUDIT I STOPPED THE BELT AND FOLLOWED THE DLN PROCEDURE. I CALLED TO MY SUPERVISOR, ERIC LOCKLIN AND TOLD HIM THAT WE HAD A HAZARDOUS LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE BELT IN MY WORK AREA. AS I PROCEEDED TO THE SPILL CART TO DON PPE MR LOCKLIN TOLD ME THAT HE WANTED TO SPEAK TO ME AFTER THE SHIFT AND THAT IF I WANTED UNION REPRESENTATION I SHOULD GET IT. IN A RATHER CONFUSED STATE I PUT ON PPE AND RETURNED TO THE BELT. MEANWHILE MR LOCKLIN HAD RETRIEVED THE PACKAGE WITHOUT ANY PPE, PUSHED IT UP THE BELT WITHOUT A SPILL TUB THROUGH ANOTHER EMPLOYEES WORK AREA GAVE IT TO ME AND TOLD ME TO PROCESS IT RIGHT THEN. I ADVISED HIM TAT THE DOCUMENTATION AND PROCESSING OF A HAZARDOUS LEAKER WAS QUITE LONG AND EXTENSIVE AND AFTER MUCH CONFUSION BY THE ENTIRE SHIFT I WAS INSTRUCTED TO RETURN TO MY PRELOAD POSITION. AFTER THE SHIFT I REQUESTED MR. LOCKLIN  ADVISED ME ON THE LEAKING PACKAGE SIMPLY TO CLARIFY WHAT I WAS BEING INSTRUCTED TO DO. THE SPILL WAS RELATIVELY SMALL... 3 TO 6 OUNCES RESULTING IN A CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD BOX I INDICATED THAT I WAS SUPPOSED TO PROCESS THE PACKAGE ACCORDING TO THE DMP PROCEDURE. I TOLD HIM THAT IRONICALLY THE CARDBOARD WOULD PROBABLY DRY BUT THAT HE WOULD HAVE TO DISCUSS THAT WITH ASLENE MORSE, THE SAFETY AND COMPLIANCE OFFICER. WE HAD A SIMILAR INCIDENT YEARS AGO.... THE OUT COME OF WHICH I DO NOT RECALL. MR LOCKLIN THEN TOLD ME THAT I SHOULD TIGHTEN THE CAPS AND FORWARD THE PACKAGE. I DID AS INSTRUCTED AND ENTERED THE PACKAGE INTO ECS AS AN AM AS I COULD NOT PROCESS IT AS DAMAGE. ON MONDAY MORNING WHEN THE STAINED PACKAGE HAD NOT DRIED, MR LOCKLIN INSTRUCTED ME TO PROCESS THE PACKAGE ACCORDING TO DMP PROCEDURE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. INSPECTION NOTED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN THE WELL OF DOUBLE STACK CAR DTTX 720119-A. STRONG ODORS WERE NOTED AROUND THE CONTAINER AND THERE WERE SIGNS THAT PRODUCT HAD LEAKED, HOWEVER, THE AREA AROUND THE REAR DOORS WAS DRY. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND CONTAINED PENDING INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, NOTED EXTREMELY STRONG ODORS FROM THE INTERIOR OF THE CONTAINER. THE LADING OF 5 GALLON PAILS WAS SECURED WITH TY-GARD AT THE REAR, AND ALSO BAYED OUT NEAR THE CENTER OF THE LOAD. BOTH SECTIONS OF THE TY-GARD WERE LOOSE AND HANGING, INDICATING LOAD SHIFT. THE PAILS WERE PALLETIZED AND STRETCH WRAPPED. HONEYCOMBED CARDBOARD DIVIDERS HAD BEEN PLACE LONGITUDINALLY DOWN THE CENTER LINE OF THE CONTAINER TO TAKE UP THE VOID BETWEEN THE PALLETS. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED BY RAIL, PER THE AAR BOE 6C. DUE TO THE LADING SHIFTING, THE STRETCH WRAP WAS NOT ADEQUATE TO HOLD THE PAILS TO THE PALLETS, CAUSING THEM TO TOPPLE INTO EACH OTHER AND THE CARDBOARD FILLER, WHICH COLLAPSED. 13 PAILS OF ACETONE WERE FOUND TO BE EMPTY, 24 PAILS LEAKING, 33 PAILS DAMAGED, AND 108 PAILS IN GOOD CONDITION. 2 PAILS OF PAINT THINNER WERE FOUND TO BE EMPTY, 18 PAILS LEAKING, 18 PAILS DAMAGED, AND 216 PAILS IN GOOD CONDITION. ALL THE LEAKING AND DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY TO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE. RMCC MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.

UPON MY ARRIVAL, MET WITH MEMBERS OF THE RIALTO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SAN BERMARDINO HAZMAT. INSPECTION OF THE CAR DID NOT DEVELOP ANY VISABLE SIGNS OF PRODUCT LEAKAGE. INSPECTION OF THE FLANGE ON THE LIQUID LINE DID NOTE TWO OF THE FOUR NUTS FOR THE SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE MISSING, AND THE TWO NUTS THAT WERE IN PLACE COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. THERE WAS NO SIGN OF FRESH PRODUCT ANY WHERE ON THE TOP WORKING AREA OF THE CAR. THE MISSING NUTS WERE REPLACED, AND ALL PROPERLY TIGHTENED. WHILE INSPECTING THE CAR, A TRAIL OF LIQUID DROPS WERE NOTED ON BOTH SIDES OF THE TRACKS JUST WEST OF THE SUBJECT CAR. THE LIQUID WAS SOMEWHAT FRESH AND PH'ED, INDICATING THE MATERIAL WAS AN ACID. INSPECTION OF THE YARD FAILED TO LOCATE ANY ACID TANK CARS THAT WERE LEAKING. AS THIS CAR WAS A RESIDUE EMPTY. IT IS VERY UNLIKELY THIS CAR WAS THE SOURCE OF THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. THE CAR WAS PLACED ON HOLD FOR A MECHANICAL INSPECTION. ONCE COMPLETED THE CAR WILL BE RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  RMCC MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.
